# Documentation Rules

- Document code when the purpose, inputs, outputs, or business context would not be obvious to a new contributor.
- All functions should include a short explanation of purpose and inputs when the behavior is not self-evident.
- Keep comments concise, accurate, and focused on intent rather than restating the code line by line.
- Update documentation alongside behavior changes so docs do not drift from the implementation.

## Function Documentation

- Every function must have comments when its purpose, assumptions, or inputs are not immediately clear from the code.
- Prefer short descriptions that explain what the function does, what inputs it expects, and any important side effects.
- Avoid noisy comments that simply restate obvious code.

## README Expectations

- Update the README when changes affect setup, workflows, architecture, business rules, or user-facing behavior.
- The README should cover both technical context and business logic so new joiners can understand how the project works.
- Include enough onboarding detail for a new contributor to understand the project's purpose, main flows, and development setup.

Example:

```text
All functions must include a short explanation of purpose and inputs.
README must be updated for both technical and business logic so new joiners can understand the project.
```
